      <div class="stat"><div class="val">30 Days</div><div class="label">Wash Sale Window</div></div>
      <div class="stat"><div class="val">∞</div><div class="label">Loss Carry-Forward</div></div>
    </div>

    <!-- Section 1: What It Is -->
    <section>
      <h2>What Is Tax-Loss Harvesting?</h2>
      <div class="explainer">
        <h3>The Core Concept</h3>
        <p>Tax-loss harvesting is an investment strategy where you <strong>sell a security at a loss</strong> to offset capital gains taxes, then <strong>immediately buy a similar (but not identical) investment</strong> to maintain your portfolio allocation. The IRS lets you use investment losses to reduce your tax bill — you're essentially converting paper losses into real tax savings.</p>
        <p>Harvested losses can offset: <strong>1)</strong> Capital gains dollar-for-dollar (short-term losses offset short-term gains first, then long-term gains). <strong>2)</strong> Up to $3,000 of ordinary income per year. <strong>3)</strong> Any unused losses carry forward indefinitely to future tax years.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="explainer">
        <h3>How It Works: A Concrete Example</h3>
        <p>Suppose you bought $50,000 of VTI (Vanguard Total Stock Market ETF) and it drops to $42,000 — an $8,000 unrealized loss.</p>
        <div class="example-box">
          <div class="label-sm">Tax-Loss Harvest in 3 Moves</div>
          1. Sell VTI at $42,000 → realize <span class="negative">-$8,000 loss</span><br>
          2. Immediately buy ITOT (iShares Total Stock Market) at $42,000<br>
          3. Portfolio stays fully invested in total US stock market<br><br>
          <div class="label-sm">Tax Impact (35% Bracket)</div>
          $8,000 loss × 35% tax rate = <span class="positive">$2,800 tax savings</span><br>
          If you had $5,000 in capital gains: offset fully, remaining $3,000 offsets ordinary income<br>
          Net effect: same portfolio exposure, $2,800 less in taxes
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="explainer">
        <h3>Important: Tax Deferral, Not Elimination</h3>
        <p>Tax-loss harvesting primarily <strong>defers</strong> taxes rather than eliminating them. When you swap VTI for ITOT, your cost basis in ITOT is lower ($42,000 instead of $50,000). When you eventually sell ITOT at a gain, you'll owe taxes on the larger gain. However, deferral is still valuable because: <strong>1)</strong> Time value of money — paying taxes later is better than paying now. <strong>2)</strong> You might be in a lower bracket when you sell. <strong>3)</strong> If held until death, heirs receive a stepped-up basis. <strong>4)</strong> The $3,000 ordinary income deduction is a permanent benefit.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

