      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 3: Wash Sale Rule -->
    <section>
      <h2>The Wash Sale Rule Explained</h2>
      <div class="explainer">
        <h3>What Is the Wash Sale Rule?</h3>
        <p>The wash sale rule (IRS Section 1091) disallows a tax deduction if you buy a <strong>"substantially identical"</strong> security within <strong>30 days before or after</strong> selling at a loss. This creates a <strong>61-day exclusion window</strong>: 30 days before the sale + the sale date + 30 days after.</p>
        <p>If triggered, the disallowed loss isn't gone forever — it gets <strong>added to the cost basis</strong> of the replacement security. But you lose the immediate tax benefit, which defeats the purpose of harvesting.</p>
      </div>

      <h3 style="margin-bottom:12px;">30-Day Wash Sale Timeline</h3>
      <div class="timeline">
        <div class="timeline-bar">
          <div class="timeline-zone zone-danger">No Buy Zone<br>30 days before</div>
          <div class="timeline-zone zone-sale">SELL</div>
          <div class="timeline-zone zone-danger-after">No Buy Zone<br>30 days after</div>
          <div class="timeline-zone zone-safe">Safe to<br>Repurchase</div>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-labels">
          <span>Day -30</span>
          <span>Sale Day (Day 0)</span>
          <span>Day +30</span>
          <span>Day +31 →</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-desc">
        <p><strong>The solution:</strong> Instead of repurchasing the same security, buy a <strong>similar but not substantially identical</strong> fund. For example, sell SPY (tracks S&P 500) and buy IVV (also tracks S&P 500 but from a different provider). The IRS has not ruled that different ETFs tracking the same index are "substantially identical," and this swap is widely used by robo-advisors and tax professionals.</p>
        <p><strong>Watch out:</strong> The wash sale rule applies across <strong>all your accounts</strong> — including IRAs, 401(k)s, and your spouse's accounts. If you sell VTI in your taxable account and buy VTI in your IRA within 30 days, the loss is disallowed and <em>permanently</em> lost (you can't add it to IRA cost basis).</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 4: Step-by-Step Process -->
    <section>
      <h2>Tax-Loss Harvesting: Step-by-Step</h2>
      <div class="steps">
        <div class="step-card">
          <h3>Identify Positions with Unrealized Losses</h3>
          <p>Review your taxable brokerage account for holdings that are currently below your purchase price. Focus on positions with meaningful losses — at least a few hundred dollars to justify the effort and potential trading costs.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="step-card">
          <h3>Check for Wash Sale Conflicts</h3>
          <p>Before selling, verify you haven't purchased the same security in the past 30 days and won't auto-purchase it (via dividend reinvestment, recurring investments, or in other accounts like your IRA/401k) in the next 30 days. Disable any automatic purchases of that security.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="step-card">
          <h3>Sell the Losing Position</h3>
          <p>Place a sell order for the full position. If you hold multiple tax lots purchased at different times, use specific lot identification to sell only the lots with losses (most brokers support this). This maximizes harvested losses while potentially keeping lots with gains.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="step-card">
          <h3>Immediately Buy a Replacement Security</h3>
          <p>Same day, purchase a similar but not substantially identical ETF or fund. See the swap pairs table below for common replacements. The goal is to maintain your target asset allocation and market exposure while satisfying the wash sale rule.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="step-card">
          <h3>Record the Transaction</h3>
          <p>Log the harvest date, original security, replacement security, loss amount, and the 31-day safe repurchase date. After 31+ days, you can swap back to the original security if preferred — or simply keep the replacement.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="step-card">
          <h3>Claim the Loss on Your Tax Return</h3>
          <p>Report harvested losses on Schedule D and Form 8949. Losses first offset capital gains (short-term losses against short-term gains, then long-term). Remaining net losses offset up to $3,000 of ordinary income. Any excess carries forward to the next tax year.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 5: ETF Swap Pairs Table -->
