// When NOT to Harvest
const warningsData=[
  {title:"You're in the 0% Capital Gains Bracket",desc:"If your taxable income is under ~$47,025 (single) or ~$94,050 (married filing jointly) in 2026, your long-term capital gains rate is 0%. Harvesting losses to offset gains that would be tax-free anyway wastes the loss — you'd be better off realizing gains tax-free and saving the losses for a year when you're in a higher bracket."},
  {title:"You Expect a Much Higher Future Tax Rate",desc:"Tax-loss harvesting converts current gains into future gains (through lower cost basis). If you expect to be in a significantly higher tax bracket when you eventually sell, the deferred taxes could be larger than today's savings. This is rare but worth considering for early-career high earners."},
  {title:"The Loss Is Too Small to Matter",desc:"Harvesting a $50 loss to save $12 in taxes isn't worth the effort, tracking complexity, and potential for wash sale mistakes. Focus on positions with meaningful losses — at least a few hundred dollars — especially if you're doing this manually rather than through a robo-advisor."},
  {title:"You Plan to Hold Until Death (Step-Up Basis)",desc:"If you plan to hold investments until you pass them to heirs, the cost basis resets to market value at death (stepped-up basis). This means unrealized gains are never taxed. In this scenario, harvesting losses now creates a tax benefit today but reduces the future step-up — it may be a wash or even slightly negative."},
  {title:"You'd Trigger a Wash Sale",desc:"If you can't avoid purchasing substantially identical securities across all accounts within the 61-day wash sale window, don't harvest. A botched harvest that triggers the wash sale rule gives you zero tax benefit while still realizing the loss in your portfolio records. Common traps: automatic dividend reinvestment and 401(k) contributions buying the same fund."},
  {title:"Short-Term vs Long-Term Mismatch",desc:"Be cautious about harvesting a long-term loss (taxed at 0–20% when realized) to offset short-term gains (taxed at ordinary rates up to 37%). While this works in your favor, the reverse is wasteful: don't harvest short-term losses just to carry them forward if they'll eventually offset long-term gains taxed at a lower rate. Match loss character to gain character when possible."}
];
const warningsEl=document.getElementById('warnings');
warningsData.forEach(w=>{
  warningsEl.innerHTML+=`<div class="warning-card"><h3>${w.title}</h3><p>${w.desc}</p></div>`;
});

// FAQ
const faqs=[
  {q:"What is tax-loss harvesting?",a:"Tax-loss harvesting is an investment strategy where you sell securities at a loss to offset capital gains taxes. You then reinvest in a similar (but not substantially identical) security to maintain your portfolio allocation. The harvested losses can offset capital gains dollar-for-dollar and up to $3,000 of ordinary income per year, with unused losses carried forward indefinitely."},
  {q:"What is the wash sale rule?",a:"The wash sale rule (IRS Section 1091) disallows a tax deduction on a security sold at a loss if you purchase a substantially identical security within 30 days before or after the sale. This creates a 61-day window during which you cannot repurchase the same investment. The disallowed loss gets added to the cost basis of the replacement security."},
  {q:"How much can tax-loss harvesting save me?",a:"Savings depend on your tax bracket and the size of your unrealized losses. At a 35% marginal rate with $10,000 in harvested losses, you could save $3,500 in taxes. For taxable accounts, automated tax-loss harvesting typically generates 0.5–1.5% in annual tax alpha. The savings are highest for investors in the 32–37% federal brackets with large taxable portfolios."},
  {q:"Can you tax-loss harvest in an IRA or 401(k)?",a:"No, tax-loss harvesting only works in taxable brokerage accounts. IRAs, 401(k)s, and Roth accounts are already tax-advantaged, so there is no benefit to harvesting losses. Be careful: buying a substantially identical security in your IRA within the 30-day window can trigger the wash sale rule and permanently disallow the loss."},
  {q:"What are the best ETF swap pairs for tax-loss harvesting?",a:"Common swap pairs include SPY ↔ IVV (S&P 500), VTI ↔ ITOT (total US market), VXUS ↔ IXUS (international), BND ↔ AGG (bonds), VWO ↔ IEMG (emerging markets), and VEA ↔ IEFA (developed international). The key is choosing ETFs that track similar but not identical indexes from different providers."},
  {q:"Is tax-loss harvesting worth it?",a:"Yes, for most investors with taxable accounts in the 22%+ bracket. The strategy typically generates 0.5–1.5% in annual tax savings, often exceeding robo-advisor management fees. It may not be worthwhile if you're in the 0% capital gains bracket, have a very small taxable account, or plan to hold until death for a stepped-up basis."},
  {q:"Does tax-loss harvesting work with individual stocks?",a:"Yes, and it's even more effective through direct indexing. Instead of holding an S&P 500 ETF, direct indexing buys individual stocks, allowing you to harvest losses on specific positions even when the overall market is up. Wealthfront offers direct indexing for accounts over $100,000."},
  {q:"When should you NOT harvest tax losses?",a:"Avoid harvesting when: you're in the 0% capital gains bracket, the loss is too small to justify the effort, you'd trigger a wash sale, you plan to hold until death for a stepped-up basis, or you expect to be in a significantly higher tax bracket when eventually selling the replacement security."}
];
